GWRF 12m Price Target: \(\) 270.00\(Price:\) \ \(217.02\) Upside: \(24.4\%\)

We reiterate our Buy- rating and \(\) 270\(PT on Guidewire ahead of F4Q25 earnings (9/4). On the print, we are primarily focused on net new cloud deals (already tracking\) 50\% + \(ahead of typical annual pacing), FY25 ARR and fully- ramped ARR growth, and management's initial FY26 guidance. Based on the pacing of cloud deals YTD, increasing traction of deals for the full InsuranceSuite, our F4Q checks, and the timing of ARR ramps for F4Q, we believe 1) Guidewire could report an ARR beat above historical average outperformance and 2) FRARR growth has the potential to come in at\) 20\% + \(, each supporting sustained acceleration in momentum that in our view will validate Guidewire's premium in the market.

For reference, GWRE has 38 cloud deals signed through F3Q, which is higher than FY22/23/24 (through 3 quarters) at 24/20/26 and already nearing the FY22- FY24 full year average of 40 cloud deals signed (Exhibit 1). Over the prior 19 quarters, GWRE has a median ARR beat vs. the mid- point of guidance of \(\) 5.5\(mn (Exhibit 2) while ARR has come in above the high - end of guidance in 17 of those 19 quarters. We recall that despite F3Q ARR coming in -\) \ \(16mn\) ahead of guidance (mid- point), updated FY ARR guidance implies \(\) 57mn\(of N N A R R sequentially in F4Q. \) \ \(60.5mn\) prior (both mid- points), which supports our view that F4Q will see similar momentum in net new cloud demand as the first three quarters (while also benefiting from ARR ramps that are weighted to 4Q this year). Heading into EPS, we expect total revenue \(+16\%\) , subscription & support revenue \(+29\%\) and non- GAAP operating margin of \(- 17\%\) (vs. \(- 17\%\) in 4Q24). We expect NNARR of \(-\) 61mn (vs. \(- 44mn\) in 4Q24), which we think could prove conservative if recent cloud migration trends continue. While our intragarter investor conversations have generally reflected the market's positive view of Guzewire's deal momentum and competitive position, a debate has materialized around the impact of slowing Insurer premium growth off of elevated levels post- COVID on Guzewire's reported financials. We acknowledge that such developments could have modest impacts to on- prem revenue true- ups and go- forward DWP- based entitlements in contracts (reflected in ARR), though we ultimately believe Guzewire's relatively wide DWP pricing bands (which limit the impact of market dynamics on reported metrics), accelerating net new cloud deals, and growing size of customer lands should more than offset these dynamics. While we recognize GWRE's premium valuation as shares currently trade at \(\sim 12X\) CY26 EV/Sales and \(\sim 47X\) EV/FCF vs. \(10 - 20\%\) growth software peers at \(\sim 6X / 29X\) (average), we continue to believe the long- term sustainability of market share gains, incremental near- term upside from the pace of cloud migrations, sales execution in light of improving platform referencability, and realistic near- term path to \(\) 6\(in FCF/share will continue to support premium growth- relative multiples. Additionally, shares of GWRE are down \~16\% from June highs (post F3Q EPS), which we believe creates a favorable setup for investors heading into the F4Q print. We remain Buy- rated with a\) \ \(270\) , 12- month price target. Shares of GWRE are \(+29\%\) YTD vs. the S&P 500 \(+10\%\) .

Fully- ramped ARR: During the F3Q25 earnings call, management expressed confidence in maintaining FY25 fully- ramped ARR (FRARR) growth in- line with recent performance in the high- teens (17/19% yoy in FY23/24). As we highlighted in our F3Q25 Preview, FY23/24 reported FRARR growth came in 250bps/300bps above management's initial 3Q expectations. Based on guided net new ARR for the business this year and continued cloud deal momentum that has well outpaced prior years (Exhibit 1), we see significant potential for FY25 FRARR growth coming in at \(20\%\) or higher.

We expect ARR of \(\) 1,021\(mn vs. consensus of\) \ \(1,016m\) . We expect \(\sim\) 14mn of GAAP operating income, and non- GAAP operating income of \(\) 57.7m\((- 17\%\) of revenue). For FY25, we currently estimate total revenue of \(\) 1,184.3m(+21\% yoy)\(and non - GAAP operating income of\) \ \(192.4m(- 16\%\) of revenue), both ahead of Consensus of \(\) 1,182m\(/\) \ \(191m\) , respectively. Guidewire is at the forefront of an accelerating wave of cloud modernization in the P&C insurance industry, where we estimate the large majority of direct written premium (DWP) globally is still being managed on legacy or on- premise systems. With Guidewire winning more than \(60\%\) of core system decision deals \((>75\%\) by DWP) and as an industry leader in facilitating insurers' cloud transitions globally (Guidewire has done \(\sim 40\) cloud deals per year over each of the last three years and has done 38 through F3Q25), we believe the company is well positioned to benefit from expanding cloud referencability, particularly with larger insurers. In addition, compounding technological and cost advantages through systematic, robust cloud releases should continue to put pressure on the \(\sim 50\%\) of DWP we estimate still runs on legacy, customized mainframe systems that have dominated the market for decades. Guidewire's ramping cloud monetization model provides considerable backlog for future revenue recognition which, when combined with new logo, cloud migration, and cross- sell potential in the P&C space, should lead GWRE to sustainable, mid- to- high teens \(\%\) long- term growth into its \(\sim \$ 15bn\) TAM. Management's ability to scale over cloud operations and infrastructure costs is well established to date; we expect incremental economies of scale to continue to ramp FCF margins towards leading vertical software peers over time.

Our Buy- rating and investment thesis are predicated on: 1) sustainable- to- accelerating cloud transition activity in the P&C insurance space, which lends visibility to long- term growth sustainability in excess of \(15\%\) annually; 2) effective portfolio expansion with cloud customers, both within core and emerging solutions, driving more DWP and contract value per customer; 3) maintaining a cloud innovation gap with core P&C insurance software peers through internal investment (i.e. continuous cloud releases), strategic M&A, and continued third- party integration through the company's applications marketplace (including key non- core P&C vendors like Verisk and CCC); and 4) continuing to expand margins in excess of consensus expectations, leveraging growing efficiencies across cloud functions as revenue scales. In total, we think these factors are likely to drive sustained upward revisions to consensus estimates and compounding FCF, which justify our premium multiple for GWRE.

GWRE ranks favorably in our investment framework, addressing our top two software characteristics (essential functionality, horizontal platform) through providing core system functionality while facilitating insurer cross- sell through cloud upgrades. These two elements in combination with one another are likely drivers of accelerated TAM penetration (cloud referencability, easier cross- sell), TAM expansion (e.g. Tier 3 insurers through InsuranceNow), and improving unit economics. Guidewire's industry- leadership has unlocked a more rapid pace of innovation, which has the potential to incrementally improve win rates, particularly in underpenetrated international markets. We generally believe that the essential nature of cloud core upgrades has insulated the end- market from the material growth deceleration post- 2021 that we observed across other software categories, complemented by sustainable growth in underlying industry
premiums, which also highlights asset defensibility that we continue to prefer in the current environment.
Exhibit 5: GS Emerging Software Investment Framework
Source:Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Key Catalysts to watch for: Continued cloud migration momentum, revenue uplift from prior cloud migration cohorts reaching fully- ramped ARR ( \(\sim \$ 1.06bn\) in FRARR vs. \$864mn reported ARR as of 4Q24), increased cloud demand (GWRE has done \(\sim 40\) cloud deals per year over each of the last 3 years, 38 through F3Q25), future cross/up- sell success as we estimate a majority of GWRE's current cloud customers have not adopted the full InsuranceSuite (PolicyCenter, BillingCenter, ClaimsCenter), and global DWP growth.
Our \(\) 270\(12 - month price target is based on a\) 15.5x Q5 - Q8 (NTM + 1Y) EV/Sales fundamental value, implying \~60x EV/uFCF.
Key downside risks include: 1) macro uncertainty could lead to delays in

decision- making impacting bookings pipeline, 2) risk- averse buyer profile could result in slower pace of cloud adoption impacting top- line growth, 3) lower DWP growth due to slowing inflation, decreased affordability related to premiums, or structural decline in specific insurance sub- market that could affect revenue growth, 4) longer implementation cycles could pose risk to contractual obligations around service levels, product functionality and implementation timelines.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.

Any stock not assigned as a Buy or a Sell on an Investment List with an active rating (i.e., a stock that is not Rating Suspended, Not Rated, Early- Stage Biotech, Coverage Suspended or Not Covered), is deemed Neutral. Each region manages Regional Conviction Lists, which are selected from Buy rated stocks on the respective region's Investment Lists and represent investment recommendations focused on the size of the total return potential and/or the likelihood of the realization of the return across their respective areas of coverage. The addition or removal of stocks from such Conviction Lists are managed by the Investment Review Committee or other designated committee in each respective region and do not represent a change in the analysts' investment rating for such stocks.

Total return potential represents the upside or downside differential between the current share price and the price target, including all paid or anticipated dividends, expected during the time horizon associated with the price target. Price targets are required for all covered stocks. The total return potential, price target and associated time horizon are stated in each report adding or reiterating an Investment List membership.
